body:
Thanks for the super quick fix for #4593!
Expanding the scope of Verilator on my end and found some more edge cases related to clocking blocks that Verilator disagrees with. This is a pruned down version of a pretty common pattern I have in a few of my regression tests.

There are a few internal errors in here, but all appear to be related to how loops in forked processes are verilated, so including them together in this testcase.

# Example file `test.sv`
```systemverilog
module tb();
    logic clk = 0;
    logic x;
    logic y;

    always #1ns clk = ~clk;

    assign y = x;

    default clocking cb @(posedge clk);
        output #1ns x;
        input #1step y;
    endclocking

    initial begin
        cb.x <= '0;
        ##2;
        fork
            begin
                repeat(5) begin
                    cb.x <= ~cb.y;
                    @cb;
                end
            end
            begin
                repeat(4) begin
                    ##1;
                end
            end
        join_any
        disable fork;
        $finish();
    end
endmodule
```

# Command-line & error
```bash
$ ./verilator/bin/verilator --sv --binary  test.sv
%Error-LIFETIME: test.sv:20:17: Invalid reference: Process might outlive variable `__Vrepeat0`.
                                    : ... note: In instance 'tb'
                                    : ... Suggest use it as read-only to initialize a local copy at the beginning of the process, or declare it as static. It is also possible to refer by reference to objects and their members.
   20 |                 repeat(5) begin
      |                 ^~~~~~
                 ... For error description see https://verilator.org/warn/LIFETIME?v=5.017
%Error: Internal Error: test.sv:22:22: ../V3Fork.cpp:599: Variable's lifetime is unknown. Can't determine if a capture is necessary.
                                           : ... note: In instance 'tb'
   22 |                     @cb;
      |                      ^~
```

# Version & OS
* Verilator 5.017 devel rev v5.014-234-g33c5b5feb
* Ubuntu 22.04
